- **GitHub Repository**: [LGouellec/streamiz](https://github.com/LGouellec/streamiz)
- **Latest Version**: Not specified in the search results.
- **Key Config Options**:
  - `bootstrap.servers`: List of Kafka brokers to connect to.
  - `group.id`: Consumer group ID for consumer applications.
  - `auto.offset.reset`: Behavior when there is no initial offset or if the current offset does not exist any more on the server (e.g., because that data has been deleted).
- **CLI Commands**:
  - Not explicitly provided in search results, but you can use tools like `dotnet` to create and manage .NET projects.
- **Example Usage**:
  - For a Kafka producer in .NET, you might use the following code snippet:
    ```csharp
    using Confluent.Kafka;

    var config = new ProducerConfig { BootstrapServers = "localhost:9092" };
    using (var producer = new ProducerBuilder<Null, string>(config).Build())
    {
        try
        {
            var result = await producer.ProduceAsync("my-topic", new Message<Null, string> { Value = "Hello World!" });
            Console.WriteLine($"Message sent to topic: {result.TopicPartitionOffset}");
        }
        catch (ProduceException<Null, string> e)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"Delivery failed: {e.Error.Reason}");
        }
    }
    ```
  - For a Kafka consumer in .NET, you might use the following code snippet:
    ```csharp
    using Confluent.Kafka;

    var config = new ConsumerConfig { BootstrapServers = "localhost:9092", GroupId = "my-group" };
    using (var consumer = new ConsumerBuilder<Null, string>(config).Build())
    {
        consumer.Subscribe("my-topic");

        try
        {
            while (true)
            {
                var consumeResult = consumer.Consume();
                Console.WriteLine($"Consumed message '{consumeResult.Message.Value}' at: '{consumeResult.TopicPartitionOffset}'.");
            }
        }
        catch (ConsumeException e)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"Error occured: {e.Error.Reason}");
        }
    }
    ```
